 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub175.ezboard.com/unage42.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nage42</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/4/02 2:52:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3657.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Thrust Inf</span><hr size=1> Heya;<br>
<br>
Well, most are in agreement that Infs are the best game in town as far as all around use is concerned, and many thoughts (and jabs) were exchanged.<br>
<br>
I'm actually ok with being weaker than an Inf, means I have to make up with skill.  I think we'll find that with the Inf being identified as the &quot;1337 00ber&quot; power-gamer's class to play, there will be a huge influx of people who rely on it's inhearent power rather than skill, tactics, and patients (target picking).  The only problem I have is with completely imbalancing things – DragonFang is in this category.  Letting a class that has Evade VII take more than 2 levels of Dodger is also a bit suspect (even though all assassins have it, I can feel for tanks that can’t hit at all).<br>
<br>
Change the DragonFang move to be behind-target based and change the stun effect to heavy attack speed hinder or snare.  Review the Slash moves so that the Amythist/Diamond moves are as-is, but that Diamond doesn’t have +very high to-hit but small or medium bonus instead (it shouldn’t be a guaranteed thing to make a second chain move).  In both Slash and Thrust ensure that there is a 18/39 chain off evade move that gives them a medium to-hit, medium stun (like the LA Comeback -&gt; Frosty).<br>
<br>
I’d normally take offence to the NS piercing medium stun off evade move, but I suspect that NS’s actually use this to run rather than continue tanking... and in all honesty NS’s do need something.  Given that the stun duration will be reduced with resists, I’d say let them keep it (cause they generally won’t be specing 50 Pierce and the move isn’t a high level one).<br>
<br>
Leave SB LA Double Frost in it’s nerfed form, but give the Snowquall (29) and Icy Brilliance (44) more damage (and reduce agro for PvE), these are a back-facing move, so should not effect PvP much.  Leave the pitiful ~+50 HitPoints as-is.<br>
<br>
And finally give NS and SBs 2.3 spec points... a small increase but perhaps enough to raise two or three skills up by a point or one skill up by 2 or 3 by end-game.<br>
<br>
The result of this should be that SBs are slightly more effective in PvE, Slashing Infs will still probably generally beat other assassins, but the change to DragonFang and limiting Dodger to 2 should bring the Thrust Inf back into the world of us mortals.<br>
<br>
As an aside, if we add all these two-bits up, we'd be able to pay another two-bit programmer's wages to fix all this... *cough*  just kidding.<br>
 <p>Cheers,<BR>
